# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: automotive-autosar
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] Electronic systems have become an increasingly large component of the cost of an automobile, from only around 1% of its value in 1950 to around 30% in 2010.
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] Modern electric cars rely on power electronics for the main propulsion motor control, as well as managing the battery system.
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] Future autonomous cars will rely on powerful computer systems, an array of sensors, networking, and satellite navigation, all of which will require electronics.
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] The earliest electronic systems available as factory installations were vacuum tube car radios, starting in the early 1930s.
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] The development of semiconductors after World War II greatly expanded the use of electronics in automobiles, with solid-state diodes making the automotive alternator the standard after about 1960, and the first transistorized ignition systems appearing in 1963.
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] The emergence of metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) technology led to the development of modern automotive electronics.
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] Dawon Kahng summarized in a Bell Labs memo the achievement: E.
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] Ligenza who developed the diffusion processes, and H.
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] This led to the development of the power MOSFET by Hitachi in 1969, and the single-chip microprocessor by Federico Faggin, Marcian Hoff, Masatoshi Shima and Stanley Mazor at Intel in 1971.
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] The development of MOS integrated circuit (MOS IC) chips and microprocessors made a range of automotive applications economically feasible in the 1970s.
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] In the early 1970s, the Japanese electronics industry began producing integrated circuits and microcontrollers for the Japanese automobile industry, used for in-car entertainment, automatic wipers, electronic locks, dashboard, and engine control.
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] The Ford EEC (Electronic Engine Control) system, which utilized the Toshiba TLCS-12 PMOS microprocessor, went into mass production in 1975.
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] In 1978, the Cadillac Seville featured a "trip computer" based on a 6802 microprocessor.
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] Electronically-controlled ignition and fuel injection systems allowed automotive designers to achieve vehicles meeting requirements for fuel economy and lower emissions, while still maintaining high levels of performance and convenience for drivers.
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] Today's automobiles contain a dozen or more processors, in functions such as engine management, transmission control, climate control, antilock braking, passive safety systems, navigation, and other functions.
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] The power MOSFET and the microcontroller, a type of single-chip microcomputer, led to significant advances in electric vehicle technology.
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] MOSFET power converters allowed operation at much higher switching frequencies, made it easier to drive, reduced power losses, and significantly reduced prices, while single-chip microcontrollers could manage all aspects of the drive control and had the capacity for battery management.
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] MOSFETs are used in vehicles such as automobiles, cars, trucks, electric vehicles, and smart cars.
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] MOSFETs are used for the electronic control unit (ECU), while the power MOSFET and IGBT are used as the load drivers for automotive loads such as motors, solenoids, ignition coils, relays, heaters and lamps.
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] In 2000, the average mid-range passenger vehicle had an estimated $100–200 of power semiconductor content, increasing by a potential 3–5 times for electric and hybrid vehicles.
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] As of 2017, the average vehicle has over 50 actuators, typically controlled by power MOSFETs or other power semiconductor devices.
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] Another important technology that enabled modern highway-capable electric cars is the lithium-ion battery.
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] It was invented by John Goodenough, Rachid Yazami and Akira Yoshino in the 1980s, and commercialized by Sony and Asahi Kasei in 1991.
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] The lithium-ion battery was responsible for the development of electric vehicles capable of long-distance travel, by the 2000s.
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] On average, a 2020s car has 50–150 chips, according to Chris Isidore of CNN Business.
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] One of the most demanding electronic parts of an automobile is the engine control unit (ECU).
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] Engine controls demand one of the highest real-time deadlines, as the engine itself is a very fast and complex part of the automobile.
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] Of all the electronics in any car, the computing power of the engine control unit is the highest, typically a 32-bit processor.
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] A modern car may have up to 100 ECU's and a commercial vehicle up to 40.
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] Many more engine parameters are actively monitored and controlled in real-time.
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] There are about 20 to 50 that measure pressure, temperature, flow, engine speed, oxygen level and NOx level plus other parameters at different points within the engine.
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] All these sensor signals are sent to the ECU, which has the logic circuits to do the actual controlling.
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] The ECU output is connected to different actuators for the throttle valve, EGR valve, rack (in VGTs), fuel injector (using a pulse-width modulated signal), dosing injector and more.
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] There are about 20 to 30 actuators in all.
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] These control the transmission system, mainly the shifting of the gears for better shift comfort and to lower torque interrupt while shifting.
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] Automatic transmissions use controls for their operation, and also many semi-automatic transmissions having a fully automatic clutch or a semi-auto clutch (declutching only).
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] The engine control unit and the transmission control exchange messages, sensor signals and control signals for their operation.
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] All of the above systems form an infotainment system.
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] Developmental methods for these systems vary according to each manufacturer.
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] Different tools are used for both hardware and software development.
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] These are new generation hybrid ECUs that combine the functionalities of multiple ECUs of Infotainment Head Unit, Advanced Driver Assistance Systems (ADAS), Instrument Cluster, Rear Camera/Parking Assist, Surround View Systems etc.
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] This saves on the cost of electronics as well as mechanical/physical parts like interconnects across ECUs etc.
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] There is also a more centralized control so data can be seamlessly exchanged between the systems.
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] Given the complexity of this hybrid system, a lot more rigor is needed to validate the system for robustness, safety and security.
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] For example, if the infotainment system's application which could be running an open-source Android OS is breached, there could be possibility of hackers to take control of the car remotely and potentially misuse it for anti-social activities.
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] Typically so, usage of a hardware+software enabled hypervisors are used to virtualize and create separate trust and safety zones that are immune to each other's failures or breaches.
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] Lot of work is happening in this area and potentially will have such systems soon if not already.
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] In order to minimize the risk of dangerous failures, safety-related electronic systems have to be developed following the applicable product liability requirements.
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] Disregard for, or inadequate application of these standards can lead to not only personal injuries, but also severe legal and economic consequences such as product cancellations or recalls.
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] The IEC 61508 standard, generally applicable to electrical/electronic/programmable safety-related products, is only partially adequate for automotive-development requirements.
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] Consequently, for the automotive industry, this standard is replaced by the existing ISO 26262, currently released as a Final Draft International Standard (FDIS).
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] ISO/DIS 26262 describes the entire product life-cycle of safety-related electrical/electronic systems for road vehicles.
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] It has been published as an international standard in its final version in November 2011.
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] The implementation of this new standard will result in modifications and various innovations in the automobile electronics development process, as it covers the complete product life-cycle from the concept phase until its decommissioning.
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] As more functions of the automobile are connected to short- or long-range networks, cybersecurity of systems against unauthorized modification is required.
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] With critical systems such as engine controls, transmission, airbags, and braking connected to internal diagnostic networks, remote access could result in a malicious intruder altering the function of systems or disabling them, possibly causing injuries or fatalities.
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] Every new interface presents a new "attack surface".
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] The same facility that allows the owner to unlock and start a car from a smartphone app also presents risks due to remote access.
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] Auto manufacturers may protect the memory of various control microprocessors both to secure them from unauthorized changes and also to ensure only manufacturer-authorized facilities can diagnose or repair the vehicle.
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] Systems such as keyless entry rely on cryptographic techniques to ensure "replay" or "man-in-the-middle attacks" attacks cannot record sequences to allow later break-in to the automobile.
[src:automotive-autosar/automotive-electronics] In 2015 the German general automobile club commissioned an investigation of the vulnerabilities of one manufacturer's electronics system, which could have led to such exploits as unauthorized remote unlocking of the vehicle.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] The objectives are scalability to different vehicle and platform variants, transferability of software, consideration of availability and safety requirements, cooperation between different partners, sustainable use of natural resources and maintainability during the product lifecycle.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] AUTOSAR was formed in July 2003 by Bavarian Motor Works (BMW), Robert Bosch GmbH, Continental AG, Mercedes-Benz Group AG, Siemens VDO and Volkswagen AG to develop and establish an open industry standard for the automotive electrical-electronic (E/E) architecture.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] In November 2003, the Ford Motor Company joined as a Core Partner.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] In the following December Peugeot Citroën Automobiles S.A. and the Toyota Motor Corporation followed.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] In November of the following year, General Motors Holding LLC also joined as a Core Partner.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] After Siemens VDO was acquired by Continental in February 2008, Siemens VDO is no longer independently represented as a Core Partner of AUTOSAR.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] Since 2003, AUTOSAR has provided four major versions of the standardized automotive software architecture for its Classic Platform and one release, along with the version of acceptance tests.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] In 2013, the AUTOSAR consortium introduced a continuous working mode for the Classic Platform to maintain the standard and provide selected improvements (including releases R4.2, and 1.0 of acceptance tests).
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] In 2016, work began on the Adaptive Platform.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] An initial release (17-03) was published in early 2017, followed by release 17–10 in October 2017 and release 18–03 in March 2018.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] With release 18–10 in October 2018, the major development activities were published.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] AUTOSAR aims to establish a global standard for software and methodology, enabling open E/E system architectures for future intelligent mobility.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] This vision focuses on ensuring high levels of dependability, particularly in terms of safety and security.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] AUTOSAR provides specifications for basic software modules, defines application interfaces, and builds a common development methodology based on a standardized exchange format.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] The basic software modules made available by the AUTOSAR layered software architecture can be used in vehicles from different manufacturers and electronic components from different suppliers, thereby reducing expenditures for research and development.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] Based on this principle, AUTOSAR aims to prepare for upcoming technologies.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] The motivation behind AUTOSAR is to manage the increasing complexity of software and E/E systems as their functional scope expands.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] The initiative is designed to support flexibility in product modifications, upgrades, and updates, while leveraging scalable solutions within and across product lines.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] Enhancing scalability and flexibility in the integration and transfer of functions is a key objective, aiming to improve the quality and reliability of software and E/E systems.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] The goals of AUTOSAR include addressing future vehicle requirements such as availability, safety, software upgrades, updates, and maintainability.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] AUTOSAR seeks to enhance scalability and flexibility for function integration and transfer.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] Additionally, the initiative aims to increase the use of "Commercial off the Shelf" software and hardware components across product lines, promoting software reuse.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] By accelerating development and maintenance processes, AUTOSAR intends to improve the management of product and process complexity and risk, while optimizing the costs associated with scalable systems.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] The purpose of the foundation standard is to enforce interoperability between the AUTOSAR platforms.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] The foundation contains common requirements and technical specifications (for example protocols) shared between the AUTOSAR platforms, and the common methodology.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] The AUTOSAR classic platform is the standard for embedded real-time ECUs based on OSEK.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] The architecture distinguishes between three software layers that run on a microcontroller: application, runtime environment (RTE) and basic software (BSW).
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] The application software layer is mostly hardware independent.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] Communication between software components and access to BSW happens via RTE, which represents the full interface for applications.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] Services are divided further, into functional groups representing the infrastructure for system, memory and communication services.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] One essential concept of the Classic Platform is the Virtual Functional Bus (VFB).
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] This virtual bus is an abstract set of RTEs that are not yet deployed to specific ECUs and decouples the applications from the infrastructure.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] It communicates via dedicated ports, which means that the communication interfaces of the application software must be mapped to these ports.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] The VFB handles communication within the individual ECU and between ECUs.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] From an application point of view, no detailed knowledge of lower-level technologies or dependencies is required.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] This supports hardware-independent development and usage of application software.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] The Classic Platform also enables the integration of non-AUTOSAR systems such as GENIVI, now renamed COVESA, by using the Franca Interface Definition Language (Franca IDL).
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] Standardization of functional interfaces across manufacturers and suppliers and standardization of the interfaces between the different software layers is seen as a basis for achieving the technical goals of AUTOSAR.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] Only by standardizing concrete interface contents in their physical and temporal representation allows achieving the needed integration compatibility.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] New use-cases required the development of the adaptive platform.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] One example is automated driving, in the context of which the driver temporarily and/or partially transfers responsibility for driving to the vehicle.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] Further, Car-2-X applications require interaction to vehicles and off-board systems.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] That means that the system has to provide secure on-board communication, support of cross-domain computing platforms, smartphone integration, integration of non-AUTOSAR systems, and so on.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] Also, cloud-based services will require dedicated means for security, such as secure cloud interaction and emergency vehicle preemption.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] They will enable remote and distributed services, such as remote diagnostics, over the air (OTA) update, repair, and exchange handling.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] To support dynamic deployment of customer applications and to provide an environment for applications that require high-end computing power AUTOSAR is currently standardizing the AUTOSAR Adaptive Platform.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] Its core is an operating system based on the POSIX standard.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] The operating system can be used by the application via a subset of the POSIX according to IEEE1003.13 (namely PSE51).
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] One of the key features of the Adaptive Platform is service-oriented communication since the Platform is based on the Service - Oriented Architecture.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] Adaptive AUTOSAR is developed and written using C++ which is an object-oriented programming language.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] The communication protocol used for the in-vehicle networking is SOME/IP, based on Ethernet.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] Two types of interfaces are available: services and application programming interfaces (APIs).
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] The platform consists of functional clusters which are grouped in services and the AUTOSAR adaptive platform foundation.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] Functional clusters in AUTOSAR Adaptive Platform have to have at least one instance per (virtual) machine while services may be distributed in the in-car network.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] The adaptive platform contains both specification and code.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] In comparison to the Classic Platform, AUTOSAR develops an implementation to shorten the validation cycle and illustrate the underlying concepts.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] This implementation is available to all AUTOSAR partners.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] AUTOSAR defined six different levels of membership.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] Core Partners are since 2026 AUMOVIO (AUMOVIO Germany GmbH), BMW (BMW AG), Bosch (Robert Bosch GmbH), Denso, GM (General Motors Holding LLC), Huawei (Huawei Technologies Co.Ltd.), Mercedes-Benz (Mercedes-Benz Group AG), Toyota (TMC), Vector (Vector Informatik GmbH) and VW (Volkswagen AG).
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] These companies are responsible for organization, administration and control of the AUTOSAR development partnership.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] Within this core, the executive board defines the overall strategy and roadmap.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] The Steering Committee manages day-to-day non-technical operations and admission of partners, public relations and contractual issues.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] The chairman and Deputy of chairman, appointed for one year, represent the Steering Committee for that purpose.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] The AUTOSAR Spokesperson takes over the communication with the outside world.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] Premium Partner Plus companies support the project leader team in the various technical, organizational and everyday processes.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] They also give new strategic inputs to the project leader round.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] Premium and Development members contribute to work packages coordinated and monitored by the Project Leader Team established by the Core Partners.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] Associate partners are making use of the standard documents AUTOSAR has already released.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] Attendees are currently participating with Academic collaboration and non-commercial projects.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] Selection of vendors, including RTOS, BSW, design tools, compiler, etc.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] Vendors which provide related tools and software, e.g. for testing, diagnostics, development, etc.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] AUTOSAR takes part in various events every year.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] Furthermore the AUTOSAR Open Conference (AOC) is planned every year to network and give an overview over the newest achievements.
[src:automotive-autosar/autosar] A list of the events which are planned can be found on the AUTOSAR website.
[src:automotive-autosar/electronic-control-unit] An **electronic control unit** (**ECU**), also known as an **electronic control module** (**ECM**), is an embedded system in automotive electronics that controls one or more of the electrical systems or subsystems in a car or other motor vehicle.
[src:automotive-autosar/electronic-control-unit] These ECUs together are sometimes referred to collectively as **the car's computer** though technically they are all separate computers, not a single one.
[src:automotive-autosar/electronic-control-unit] Sometimes an assembly incorporates several individual control modules (a PCM often controls both the engine and the transmission).
[src:automotive-autosar/electronic-control-unit] Some modern motor vehicles have up to 150 ECUs.
[src:automotive-autosar/electronic-control-unit] Embedded software in ECUs continues to increase in line count, complexity, and sophistication.
[src:automotive-autosar/electronic-control-unit] Managing the increasing complexity and number of ECUs in a vehicle has become a key challenge for original equipment manufacturers (OEMs).
[src:automotive-autosar/electronic-control-unit] The development of an ECU involves both hardware and software required to perform the functions expected from that particular module.
[src:automotive-autosar/electronic-control-unit] Automotive ECU's are being developed following the V-model.
[src:automotive-autosar/electronic-control-unit] Recently the trend is to dedicate a significant amount of time and effort to develop safe modules by following standards like ISO 26262.
[src:automotive-autosar/electronic-control-unit] It is rare that a module is developed fully from scratch.
[src:automotive-autosar/electronic-control-unit] The design is generally iterative and improvements are made to both the hardware and software.
[src:automotive-autosar/electronic-control-unit] The development of most ECUs is carried out by Tier 1 suppliers based on specifications provided by the OEM.
[src:automotive-autosar/electronic-control-unit] As part of the development cycle, manufacturers perform detailed FMEAs and other failure analyses to catch failure modes that can lead to unsafe conditions or driver annoyance.
[src:automotive-autosar/electronic-control-unit] Extensive testing and validation activities are carried out as part of the production part approval process to gain the confidence of the hardware and software.
[src:automotive-autosar/electronic-control-unit] On-board diagnostics or OBD help provide specific data related to which system or component failed or caused a failure during run time and help perform repairs.
[src:automotive-autosar/electronic-control-unit] Some people may wish to modify their ECU so as to be able to add or change functionality.
[src:automotive-autosar/electronic-control-unit] However modern ECUs come equipped with protection locks to prevent users from modifying the circuit or exchange chips.
[src:automotive-autosar/electronic-control-unit] The protection locks are a form of digital rights management (DRM), the circumventing of which is illegal in certain jurisdictions.
[src:automotive-autosar/embedded-software] A precise and stable characteristic feature is that no or not all functions of embedded software are initiated/controlled via a human interface, but through machine-interfaces instead.
[src:automotive-autosar/embedded-software] Manufacturers build embedded software into the electronics of cars, telephones, modems, robots, appliances, toys, security systems, pacemakers, televisions and set-top boxes, and digital watches, for example.
[src:automotive-autosar/embedded-software] This software can be very simple, such as lighting controls running on an 8-bit microcontroller with a few kilobytes of memory with the suitable level of processing complexity determined with a Probably Approximately Correct Computation framework (a methodology based on randomized algorithms).
[src:automotive-autosar/embedded-software] However, embedded software can become very sophisticated in applications such as routers, optical network elements, airplanes, missiles, and process control systems.
[src:automotive-autosar/embedded-software] Unlike standard computers that generally use operating systems such as macOS, Windows or Linux, embedded software may use no operating system.
[src:automotive-autosar/embedded-software] When they do use one, a wide variety of operating systems can be chosen from, typically a real-time operating system.
[src:automotive-autosar/embedded-software] Code for embedded software is typically written in C or C++, but various high-level programming languages, such as C#, Java, Python and JavaScript, are now also in common use to target microcontrollers and embedded systems.
[src:automotive-autosar/embedded-software] Assembly languages are often used too, especially in booting and interrupt handling.
[src:automotive-autosar/embedded-software] Ada is used in some military and aviation projects.
[src:automotive-autosar/embedded-software] Most consumers are familiar with application software that provide functionality on a computer.
[src:automotive-autosar/embedded-software] However embedded software is often less visible, but no less complicated.
[src:automotive-autosar/embedded-software] Unlike application software, embedded software has fixed hardware requirements and capabilities, and addition of third-party hardware or software is strictly controlled.
[src:automotive-autosar/embedded-software] Embedded software needs to include all needed device drivers at manufacturing time, and the device drivers are written for the various hardware devices.
[src:automotive-autosar/embedded-software] The software is highly dependent on the CPU and specific chips chosen.
[src:automotive-autosar/embedded-software] Most embedded software engineers have at least a passing knowledge of reading schematics, and reading data sheets for components to determine usage of registers and communication system.
[src:automotive-autosar/embedded-software] Conversion between decimal, hexadecimal and binary is useful as well as using bit manipulation.
[src:automotive-autosar/embedded-software] Web applications are often used for managing hardware, although XML files and other output may be passed to a computer for display.
[src:automotive-autosar/embedded-software] File systems with folders are typically used, however SQL databases are often absent.
[src:automotive-autosar/embedded-software] Software development requires use of a cross compiler, which runs on a computer but produces executable code for the target device.
[src:automotive-autosar/embedded-software] Debugging requires use of an in-circuit emulator, and debugging hardware such as JTAG or SWD debuggers.
[src:automotive-autosar/embedded-software] Software developers often have access to the complete kernel (OS) source code.
[src:automotive-autosar/embedded-software] Size of the storage memory and RAM can vary significantly.
[src:automotive-autosar/embedded-software] Some systems run in 16 KB of Flash and 4 KB of RAM with a CPU operating at 8 MHz, other systems can rival contemporary computers.
[src:automotive-autosar/embedded-software] These space requirements lead to more work being done in C or embedded C++, instead of C++.
[src:automotive-autosar/embedded-software] Interpreted languages like BASIC (while e.g.
[src:automotive-autosar/embedded-software] Parallax Propeller can use compiled BASIC) and Java (Java ME Embedded 8.3 is available for e.g.
[src:automotive-autosar/embedded-software] ARM Cortex-M4, Cortex-M7 microcontrollers and older ARM11 used in Raspberry Pi and Intel Galileo Gen.
[src:automotive-autosar/embedded-software] 2) are not commonly used; while an implementation of the interpreted Python 3 language – MicroPython – is however available expressly for microcontroller use, e.g.
[src:automotive-autosar/embedded-software] 32-bit ARM-based (such as BBC micro:bit) and 16-bit PIC microcontrollers.
[src:automotive-autosar/embedded-software] Communications between processors and between one processor and other components are essential.
[src:automotive-autosar/embedded-software] Besides direct memory addressing, hardware level common protocols include I²C, SPI, serial ports, 1-Wires, Ethernets, and USB.
[src:automotive-autosar/embedded-software] Communications protocols designed for use in embedded systems are available as closed source from companies including InterNiche Technologies and CMX Systems.
[src:automotive-autosar/embedded-software] Open-source protocols stem from uIP, lwip, and others.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] A **real-time operating system** (**RTOS**) is an operating system (OS) for real-time computing applications that processes data and events that have critically defined time constraints.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] An RTOS mainly targets resource constrained devices like microcontrollers.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] It is distinct from a time-sharing operating system, such as Unix, which manages the sharing of system resources with a scheduler, data buffers, or fixed task prioritization in multitasking or multiprogramming environments.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] All operations must verifiably complete within given time and resource constraints or else the RTOS will fail safe.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] Real-time operating systems are event-driven and preemptive, meaning the OS can monitor the relevant priority of competing tasks, and make changes to the task priority.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] A key characteristic of an RTOS is the level of its consistency concerning the amount of time it takes to accept and complete an application's task; the variability is "jitter".
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] The chief design goal is not high throughput, but rather a guarantee of a soft or hard performance category.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] An RTOS that can usually or generally meet a deadline is a soft real-time OS, but if it can meet a deadline deterministically it is a hard real-time OS.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] An RTOS has an advanced algorithm for scheduling.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] Scheduler flexibility enables a wider, computer-system orchestration of process priorities, but a real-time OS is more frequently dedicated to a narrow set of applications.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] Key factors in a real-time OS are minimal interrupt latency and minimal thread switching latency; a real-time OS is valued more for how quickly or how predictably it can respond than for the amount of work it can perform in a given period of time.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] Time sharing designs switch tasks more often than strictly needed, but give smoother multitasking, giving the illusion that a process or user has sole use of a machine.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] Early CPU designs needed many cycles to switch tasks during which the CPU could do nothing else useful.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] Because switching took so long, early OSes tried to minimize wasting CPU time by avoiding unnecessary task switching.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] Blocked (waiting for an event, I/O for example).
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] Most tasks are blocked or ready most of the time because generally only one task can run at a time per CPU core.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] The number of items in the ready queue can vary greatly, depending on the number of tasks the system needs to perform and the type of scheduler that the system uses.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] On simpler non-preemptive but still multitasking systems, a task has to give up its time on the CPU to other tasks, which can cause the ready queue to have a greater number of overall tasks in the ready to be executed state (resource starvation).
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] If there are never more than a few tasks on the ready list, then a doubly linked list of ready tasks is likely optimal.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] If the ready list usually contains only a few tasks but occasionally contains more, then the list should be sorted by priority, so that finding the highest priority task to run does not require traversing the list.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] Instead, inserting a task requires walking the list.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] During this search, preemption should not be inhibited.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] Long critical sections should be divided into smaller pieces.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] If an interrupt occurs that makes a high priority task ready during the insertion of a low priority task, that high priority task can be inserted and run immediately before the low priority task is inserted.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] The critical response time, sometimes called the flyback time, is the time it takes to queue a new ready task and restore the state of the highest priority task to running.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] In a well-designed RTOS, readying a new task will take 3 to 20 instructions per ready-queue entry, and restoration of the highest-priority ready task will take 5 to 30 instructions.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] In advanced systems, real-time tasks share computing resources with many non-real-time tasks, and the ready list can be arbitrarily long.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] In such systems, a scheduler ready list implemented as a linked list would be inadequate.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] A multitasking operating system like Unix is poor at real-time tasks.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] The scheduler gives the highest priority to jobs with the lowest demand on the computer, so there is no way to ensure that a time-critical job will have access to enough resources.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] Multitasking systems must manage sharing data and hardware resources among multiple tasks.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] It is usually unsafe for two tasks to access the same specific data or hardware resource simultaneously.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] General-purpose operating systems usually do not allow user programs to mask (disable) interrupts, because the user program could control the CPU for as long as it is made to.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] Some modern CPUs do not allow user mode code to disable interrupts as such control is considered a key operating system resource.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] Many embedded systems and RTOSs, however, allow the application itself to run in kernel mode for greater system call efficiency and also to permit the application to have greater control of the operating environment without requiring OS intervention.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] On single-processor systems, an application running in kernel mode and masking interrupts is the lowest overhead method to prevent simultaneous access to a shared resource.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] While interrupts are masked and the current task does not make a blocking OS call, the current task has *exclusive* use of the CPU since no other task or interrupt can take control, so the critical section is protected.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] When the task exits its critical section, it must unmask interrupts; pending interrupts, if any, will then execute.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] Temporarily masking interrupts should only be done when the longest path through the critical section is shorter than the desired maximum interrupt latency.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] Typically this method of protection is used only when the critical section is just a few instructions and contains no loops.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] This method is ideal for protecting hardware bit-mapped registers when the bits are controlled by different tasks.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] When the shared resource must be reserved without blocking all other tasks (such as waiting for Flash memory to be written), it is better to use mechanisms also available on general-purpose operating systems, such as a mutex and OS-supervised interprocess messaging.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] Such mechanisms involve system calls, and usually invoke the OS's dispatcher code on exit, so they typically take hundreds of CPU instructions to execute, while masking interrupts may take as few as one instruction on some processors.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] A (non-recursive) mutex is either **locked** or unlocked.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] When a task has locked the mutex, all other tasks must wait for the mutex to be unlocked by its *owner* - the original thread.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] A task may set a timeout on its wait for a mutex.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] There are several well-known problems with mutex based designs such as priority inversion and deadlocks.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] In priority inversion a high priority task waits because a low priority task has a mutex, but the lower priority task is not given CPU time to finish its work.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] A typical solution is to have the task that owns a mutex 'inherit' the priority of the highest waiting task.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] But this simple approach gets more complex when there are multiple levels of waiting: task *A* waits for a mutex locked by task *B*, which waits for a mutex locked by task *C*.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] Handling multiple levels of inheritance causes other code to run in high priority context and thus can cause starvation of medium-priority threads.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] In a deadlock, two or more tasks lock mutex without timeouts and then wait forever for the other task's mutex, creating a cyclic dependency.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] The simplest deadlock scenario occurs when two tasks alternately lock two mutex, but in the opposite order.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] Deadlock is prevented by careful design.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] The other approach to resource sharing is for tasks to send messages in an organized message passing scheme.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] In this paradigm, the resource is managed directly by only one task.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] When another task wants to interrogate or manipulate the resource, it sends a message to the managing task.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] Although their real-time behavior is less crisp than semaphore systems, simple message-based systems avoid most protocol deadlock hazards, and are generally better-behaved than semaphore systems.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] However, problems like those of semaphores are possible.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] Priority inversion can occur when a task is working on a low-priority message and ignores a higher-priority message (or a message originating indirectly from a high priority task) in its incoming message queue.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] Protocol deadlocks can occur when two or more tasks wait for each other to send response messages.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] Since an interrupt handler blocks the highest priority task from running, and since real-time operating systems are designed to keep thread latency to a minimum, interrupt handlers are typically kept as short as possible.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] The interrupt handler defers all interaction with the hardware if possible; typically all that is necessary is to acknowledge or disable the interrupt (so that it won't occur again when the interrupt handler returns) and notify a task that work needs to be done.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] This can be done by unblocking a driver task through releasing a semaphore, setting a flag or sending a message.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] A scheduler often provides the ability to unblock a task from interrupt handler context.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] An OS maintains catalogues of objects it manages such as threads, mutexes, memory, and so on.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] Updates to this catalogue must be strictly controlled.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] For this reason, it can be problematic when an interrupt handler calls an OS function while the application is in the act of also doing so.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] The OS function called from an interrupt handler could find the object database to be in an inconsistent state because of the application's update.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] There are two major approaches to deal with this problem: the unified architecture and the segmented architecture.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] RTOSs implementing the unified architecture solve the problem by simply disabling interrupts while the internal catalogue is updated.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] The downside of this is that interrupt latency increases, potentially losing interrupts.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] The segmented architecture does not make direct OS calls but delegates the OS related work to a separate handler.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] This handler runs at a higher priority than any thread but lower than the interrupt handlers.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] The advantage of this architecture is that it adds very few cycles to interrupt latency.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] As a result, OSes which implement the segmented architecture are more predictable and can deal with higher interrupt rates compared to the unified architecture.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] Similarly, the System Management Mode on x86 compatible hardware can take a lot of time before it returns control to the operating system.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] Memory allocation is more critical in a real-time operating system than in other operating systems.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] First, for stability there cannot be memory leaks (memory that is allocated but not freed after use).
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] The device should work indefinitely, without ever needing a reboot.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] For this reason, dynamic memory allocation is frowned upon.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] Whenever possible, all required memory allocation is specified statically at compile time.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] Another reason to avoid dynamic memory allocation is memory fragmentation.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] With frequent allocation and releasing of small chunks of memory, a situation may occur where available memory is divided into several sections and the RTOS cannot allocate a large enough continuous block of memory, although there is enough free memory.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] Secondly, speed of allocation is important.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] A standard memory allocation scheme scans a linked list of indeterminate length to find a suitable free memory block, which is unacceptable in a RTOS since memory allocation has to occur within a certain amount of time.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] Because mechanical disks have much longer and more unpredictable response times, swapping to disk files is not used for the same reasons as RAM allocation discussed above.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] The simple fixed-size-blocks algorithm works quite well for simple embedded systems because of its low overhead.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] While all RTOSes are able to run on microcontrollers they have ports for, some RTOSes like Zephyr are capable of abstracting even further a number of device drivers like External Flash, I2C devices or internal peripherals like UART commands and sleep modes.
[src:automotive-autosar/real-time-operating-system] This helps offload the need for a developer to create drivers and instead a set of APIs are given for unsupported drivers to be ported over while supported ones are ready for use within the application code.
